    2. Create a fit for each kid using lmList in nlme package. (The intervals command creates 95% CIs for each kid’s intercept and slope.)

      ## Loading required package: nlme

      I see more spread in Intercepts than in slopes. Slopes line up well right over the zero point. There is more evidence of intercept variation than of variation of slope from one kid to another.

    3. and d. Extract coefficient vectors for each kid and obtain the two predictors we need.
      Obtain estimates for the whole population by fitting a model for intercept as a function of initial age and treatment, then fitting a similar model for slopes. Plot these fits and their ``data points’’ (in quotes because they are estimates, not data).

      Plot of individuals slopes and intercepts shows little relationship. We then look for treatment and age effects on intercepts and slopes._

      Intercepts are approximate cd4 measurements taken at the time kids come in for their first visit. I would expect to see no treatment effect, however the summary results tell me that the treated group has a higher intercept than the control group (0.48 is 2.3 SEs from 0). The intercept depends on base age, because the kids all were exposed to HIV at birth, and the older they are at first visit, the more chance the disease has had to knock down their CD4 counts. The effect estimate is -0.12 with SE of 0.05.

      Slopes are generally negative, as HIV does reduce CD4 counts. Neither base age (estimate of 0.02 with SE 0.04) nor treatment (estimate of -0.02 with SE 0.17) seem to have much effect on the slope. I hope that this was an early trial. Now we do have drug cocktails which can indefinitely delay effects of HIV.

  3. Exercise 12.2 uses the same data, but now fitting with random effects.

    1. Predict CD4% as a function of time using random intercepts and slopes for each child (both R and SAS).
      - Interpret the “fixed” intercept and time effect.
      - Is this model an improvement over the simpler “random intercept – fixed slope” model?

      ## refitting model(s) with ML (instead of REML)

      _ Yes, adding the random slope does improve the fit according to a \(\chi^2\) test on 2 df with very very small p-value. An approximate 95% CI for the slope over one year (after centering) is (-0.42, -0.21), which says that square root percent CD4 is decreasing. Alternately we could report the estimate and its SE as -0.370778 (0.0682968). SAS _

    2. Include age at baseline and treatment as fixed effects. Do they improve the model? (Both R and SAS).

      ## refitting model(s) with ML (instead of REML)

      From R the approximate 95% CI’s are (-0.01, 0.77) for treatment and (-.192, -0.02) for baseage. The first barely contains 0, so there weak evidence that treatment does increase CD4 percent and moderately strong evidence that the effect of base age is negative. SAS gives

    3. These data are noisy, so we don’t get as obvious a picture of shrinkage as in Gelman’s radon data, but we’ll build the plot anyway. In either R or SAS provide a plot which shows the intercept estimates for each child plotted over initial age. Add an arrow (or can you think of a better way?) to show where they move to (how each one changes) when we fit them as random effects.

      R Code

      setwd("/home/jimrc/classes/stat506/homework/assn3/")
cd4 <- read.csv("http://www.math.montana.edu/~jimrc/classes/stat505/data/mycd4.csv")
cd4$vdate <- as.Date(cd4$vdate)
require(lattice)
xyplot(sqrt(cd4pct) ~ I(visage-baseage),cd4, group=newpid,type=c("p","r"))
       require(nlme)
 cd4.kidfit <- lmList(sqrt(cd4pct) ~ I(visage-baseage)|factor(newpid),data=subset(cd4,!is.na(baseage))[,-9])
 plot(intervals(cd4.kidfit))
       intercepts <- summary(cd4.kidfit)$coefficients[,1,1]
 slopes <- summary(cd4.kidfit)$coefficients[,1,2]
 plot(slopes~intercepts)
 age1 <- with(subset(cd4,!is.na(baseage)), tapply(baseage, newpid,min))
  trt <- with(subset(cd4,!is.na(baseage)), tapply(treatmnt, newpid,min))
 summary(intFit <- lm(intercepts ~ age1 + factor(trt)))
 summary(slopeFit <- lm(slopes ~ age1 + factor(trt)))
      par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(intercepts ~ age1 ,col=trt, pch=trt)
legend("topright",pch=1:2,c("control","treated"),bty="n",col=1:2,lty=1:2)
abline(intFit, 1:2)
abline(sum(coef(intFit)[c(1,3)]), coef(intFit)[2],col=2,lty=2)
plot(slopes ~ age1 ,col=trt)
legend("topright",pch=1:2,c("control","treated"),bty="n",col=1:2,lty=1:2)
abline(slopeFit, 1:2)
abline(sum(coef(slopeFit)[c(1,3)]), coef(slopeFit)[2],col=2,lty=2)

cd4$adjage <- with(cd4, visage-baseage)
write.csv(cd4, file = "cd4-4SAS.csv", row.names=FALSE, quote=FALSE, na=".")

      SAS Code

       Proc import  datafile="/folders/myfolders/cd4-4SAS.csv"
    out=cd4   dbms=dlm    replace;
    delimiter=",";
    getnames=YES;
    run;
 /* Proc Print ;
 run; */
  data cd4;
    set cd4;
      sqrtPct = sqrt(cd4pct);
  run;
      
  PROC REG data = cd4  outest= cd4parms noprint;
    by newpid;   
    model  sqrtPct = adjage;
 run;
   Proc means data = cd4  noprint;
    var baseage treatmnt;
    class newpid;
    output out=kidlevel mean = mean(baseage) = trt;
  run;
  
  data kidlevel;
   set kidlevel;
   keep newpid baseage treatmnt;
  run;
 data kidlevel;
  merge kidlevel cd4parms;
  by newpid;
  keep intercept adjage baseage treatmnt 
run; 
   
 proc glm data = kidlevel  plots = ancovaplot;
   class treatmnt;
   model intercept adjage = baseage treatmnt;
  run;
  proc print;
  run;
